= Implement Gospriemka (State Inspection Reform)

For decades, Soviet factories have prioritized quantity over quality, producing vast amounts of poorly made goods that clog warehouses as consumers seek foreign imports. The Soviet economy, bound by rigid central planning, measures success by production quotas rather than consumer satisfaction. In response, General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev introduces *Gospriemka*, a sweeping quality control reform that places state inspectors directly in enterprises to reject substandard products and enforce higher manufacturing standards.

Gorbachev, drawing inspiration from Leninâ€™s Workerâ€™s Inspection, believes this reform will improve Soviet industry and modernize socialism. However, hardliners warn that the sudden crackdown on defective goods will disrupt supply chains, create shortages, and anger factory managers. Reformists argue that without it, the Soviet economy will remain uncompetitive.

